That's what drives her.
It's not over until you run.
"It is not uncommon for traffickers to demand a sexual act for a bottle of water, for example", says Bahr.
And the women are alone, they're not protected by their families.
If you think that the end will be crazy when they arrive in Germany, Bahr says.
Here again, single women in refugee shelters are often treated as inferior and, in the worst cases, abused.
As a result, she estimates that about 90 percent of the women living in the shelter in the north of Munich are traumatized.
"Some of the children were probably not born voluntarily".
Many women are so used to not saying anything.
"Or they don't dare to talk about what they've experienced openly because they're too ashamed".
Since they often cannot help themselves, more accommodation is needed for them alone, Bahr says.
In Bavaria, the seven county governments are responsible for the accommodation of refugees.
