It's fascinating to watch the world change.
The fact that teenagers and children no longer go out to play but instead prefer to spend their free time staring at screens has been a source of much complaint over the past decade.
Pokemon Go is about getting people off the couch and getting them to be more active.
Screen time was limited to television, then video games, and finally smartphones.
So it's great to see that technology and outdoor activities are not mutually exclusive.
I am referring, of course, to the Pokémon Go craze, an app based on the characters originally created for video games in the 1990s (later turned into a cartoon series, playing cards and other spin-offs).
Like many pop culture phenomena, interest in the game declined slightly before its release in the US, Australia and New Zealand in early July.
The launch in other countries was delayed by the massive demand that overloaded the servers.
Within days, Pokémon Go had more users than Tinder and almost as many as Twitter.
How does it work?
In short, players go out with their smartphones and look for Pokémon that are tracked with a GPS and, once found, can be "photographed" (via a screenshot on the phone) or "captured".
A generation that played the game when they were younger joined the craze and jumped in search of the couch.
In the United States, the game has led to a significant increase in the number of steps taken by the "average" person each day.
Cardiogram, an app for the Apple Watch that tracks 35,000 users, recently reported to the Washington Post that within two days of the game's launch, the number of people tracked who exercise 30 minutes a day jumped from 45 percent to 53 percent.
The company doesn't know which of them is playing Pokémon Go - it just sees the raw data to improve performance.
Many public health education campaigns that encourage people to "take 30 minutes", "get off the couch", and "be active every day" have fallen on deaf ears because many public health messages are boring and come from people who look miserable.
Nevertheless, the importance of sport cannot be overstated.
Regular exercise reduces the risk of cancer and depression.
Physical activity helps control weight, high blood pressure, diabetes, and a long list of benefits that is too long to list here.
But the wonderful thing about Pokémon Go is that it gets people to do something outdoors that they enjoy.
Thus, three pillars of health are covered - exercise, fresh air and sunshine, and fun.
Some people even make new friends while hunting.
As usual, there are grumpy game-breakers who always have to complain about something.
And yes, someone could run into a door.
What's the matter?
There's been a breakthrough.
Even though smartphone apps like Fitbit were able to track our activity earlier, they didn't give us a reason to exercise like this game does.
The new thing will lose its appeal and use will fade with time.
But because of Pokémon's success, there will be more games that will combine apps and virtual reality with being active in the real world, helping many people on the hunt to be more active, fitter and healthier.
