The £2-a-day drug that can reduce heart attack risk
Thousands of heart attack patients will benefit from a £2 a day drug after authorities recommended giving it to more people over a longer period.
The anticoagulant medicine Ticagrelor reduces the risk of repeated heart attacks in people with heart disease.
The medicine is given for 12 months after a heart attack, which reduces the risk of a stroke or another heart attack.
The NHS regulator NICE has recommended taking it for four years to further reduce the risk of cardiovascular problems.
The NHS regulator NICE has recommended taking it for four years to further reduce the risk of cardiovascular problems.
About 140,000 people have a heart attack every year, and a quarter of them have another heart attack or stroke.
Heart attacks and strokes are caused by accumulations of fatty material in the arterial walls that form the linings.
When the lining breaks off, it can cause a blood clot that clogs the blood flow to the heart, causing a heart attack.
When the clot dislodges, it can flow through the bloodstream and block the blood flow to the brain, causing a stroke.
People who have already had a heart attack are at a higher risk of having another one.
Ticagrelor, which is made by the UK company AstraZeneca and sold under the trade name Brilique, reduces this risk by making it less likely that blood clots will form.
The draft NICE guidance published today recommends a 12-month dose of 90mg of Ticagrelor followed by 60mg with aspirin twice daily for the next three years.
Professor Carole Longson, director of the NICE Health Technology Assessment Centre, said: "Despite the availability of secondary prevention, a quarter of all people who have had a heart attack have another heart attack or stroke, often with disastrous consequences".
The fear of another heart attack can have a significant negative impact on a person's quality of life.
Experience shows that Ticagrelor, when used in combination with aspirin, is effective in reducing further heart attacks and strokes in people who have already had a heart attack.
By making a preliminary recommendation for Ticagrelor, we are pleased to be able to expand the treatment options available to thousands of people who can benefit from it.
Information on the efficacy and safety of Ticagrelor - especially the risk of bleeding - is limited to a maximum of three years, and the draft guidance does not recommend treatment beyond this period.
