Snapchat's "anime" effect criticized as Asian cartoon
Snapchat says this filter is anime-inspired, but some observers say it's racially insensitive.
With its filter tool, Snapchat enables its 150 million daily users to change reality and play with identities in ways that border on the absurd.
You can turn into a pineapple, a dog, or a figure that could be from a Roy Lichtenstein painting.
The filters are blunt, feature-reversing tools that create more than 30 million enhanced selfies a day.
All the wrongs are made public.
Snapchat filters have in the past attracted criticism, accusing the app of promoting blackface or white skin as a beauty ideal.
When it suggested a filter to some users this week that gave them puffy eyes, false teeth and puffy cheeks, some critics called it a racist caricature of Asians - "yellowface".
They wondered if these recurring controversies pointed to a larger problem that the company had with diversity.
The news and outrage spread widely on Wednesday, with reports from The Verge and Motherboard, a day after Snapchat announced it had disabled the feature.
The company offered an excuse: the filter was meant to be a tribute to anime characters and not a caricature of Asians.
But to outsiders who have experienced racism, the filter reminded them of hurtful clichés.
Others strongly rejected the anime comparison.
In an email, Grace Sparapani, a Korean-American art student whose tweets about the photos were widely shared, wrote that the filter was "injury and, to put it mildly, unpleasant".
She added that "it's hard to argue with the contrast between a very disgusting Asian cartoon and the filter effects.
It shows that the filter is not yellow-faced, but that the yellow-faced has been pulled to the downward extreme.
Snapchat isn't the only company that's crossing these cultural barrier wires.
American culture seems to be engaged in an endless struggle for diversity and inclusion, from conference rooms to Hollywood and the devices we all hold in our hands.
And Snapchat's large audience of young people -- who are more racially diverse than their older counterparts -- might be more likely to expect sensitivity.
When one of Snapchat's filters creates an image that is offensive to a user, "it's much harder to ignore things like that than it used to be", 25-year-old Katie Zhu said in an interview on Thursday.
On Thursday, Zhu, who works as a product manager and engineer for Medium, decided to delete her Snapchat account and urged others to do the same.
In an essay for Medium and in a telephone interview, she said that she believes that racial controversies reflect a lack of diversity in Snapchat's hiring practices.
Zhu criticized the predominantly white, all-male leadership and ended her essay with a hashtag: #DeleteSnapchat.
"Either they don't have a diverse representation of people of color in their workforce to make these decisions", said Chinese-American Zhu, "or they have people of color working there who aren't in positions where they feel safe or comfortable to say anything about it".
Others share their opinion, a complaint that has largely left Snapchat unanswered.
The company does not publish figures on the diversity of its workforce and points to its status as a private company.
On Thursday, Snapchat declined to discuss the cultural backgrounds of its employees, but according to a spokesperson, the company recently hired a human resources manager who focuses on underrepresented populations and internal integration efforts.
Zhu said for her part that she will be closing her Snapchat account, adding, "I wonder if they need more users like us to be able to say that this is not OK".
Military leadership falsifies ISIS intelligence, congressional committee finds
Military officials at the United States Central Command altered intelligence to paint a more optimistic picture of the war against the so-called Islamic State in Iraq and Syria than actual conditions on the ground would have allowed, a congressional investigative committee said in a report Thursday.
The preliminary report, prepared by a task force of Republican members of the Armed Services Committee, Intelligence Committee and the Defense Budget Committee, reports deep discontent among Central Command intelligence analysts who reported how superiors changed their assessments of American efforts to fight the Islamic State.
Central Command, or Cencom for short, is the military headquarters in Tampa, Florida, that controls U.S. military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
"Intelligence typically leaked by senior Centcom commanders regularly painted a more positive picture of U.S. counterterrorism efforts than actual conditions on the ground would have allowed and was consistently more positive than analysis by other intelligence agencies", a newspaper article quoted the report as saying.
"What happened at Centcom is unacceptable - our soldiers suffer when bad analysis is presented to our political leaders", noted Ken Calvert, a Republican member of the House of Representatives.
The leadership failures at Centcom reach to the very top of the organization.
The 10-page report details persistent problems in 2014 and 2015 in the descriptions and analysis of American efforts to train Iraqi forces.
Although it provides no direct evidence that Obama administration officials gave instructions to change the reports, it shows how analysts faced pressure from their superiors to paint a more optimistic picture of the threat posed by the Islamic State, also known as ISIS or ISIL.
"During the first half of 2015, many Central Command press releases, statements and congressional testimony were significantly more positive than factual", the report noted.
For example, a Centcom official publicly announced that a military retake of Mosul could begin as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul, Iraq's second largest city, remains under the control of the Islamic State.
"After months of investigation, one thing is clear", said Mike Pompeo, a Republican congressman from Kansas, in a statement.
From mid-2014 to mid-2015, the top brass of Central Command altered intelligence reports to downplay the threat posed by ISIS in Iraq.
Republicans created the task force after being told that analysts were concerned about the manipulation of reports about the Islamic State.
The report published on Thursday will be supplemented by more detailed findings as the investigation continues.
In addition, further investigations into the Centcom reports by the Inspector General of the Department of Defense are ongoing.
Democratic members of the Intelligence Committee released their own findings on Thursday, which were consistent with some of the conclusions of the Republican Task Force.
"In 2014 and 2015, Centcom created an overly restricted process for intelligence assessment of ISIL and Iraqi security services", senior Democratic member of the committee, Representative Adam B. Schiff, said in a statement.
This process, Mr. Schiff said, "delayed the release of intelligence reports", damaged analyst morale, and "left too little room for dissent".
But Mr. Schiff and the Democrats said they found no evidence of White House interference with Centcom analysts regarding "a particular political opinion".
The preliminary results of the congressional investigation were published Tuesday by The Daily Beast.
Last August, the New York Times reported on an investigation by the Pentagon's inspector general, which was launched after complaints from Centcom analysts.
Lt. Cmdr. Patrick Evans, a Pentagon spokesman, said in a statement that the Defense Department would not comment on congressional reports while the inspector general's investigation is still ongoing.
But he also stated that "experts sometimes have quite divergent opinions on the interpretation of complex data, and that the intelligence community and the Department of Defense welcome a controversial discussion of these important national defense issues".
The investigation has implications beyond the question of a successful US-led air campaign in Iraq and Syria (a claim now being made by a growing number of DoD officials).
But last year's accusations raised the question of how much President Obama can rely on Central Command for honest assessments of military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya and other crisis regions.
Criticism of the Islamic State's intelligence is reminiscent of a dispute more than a decade ago when a Centcom analyst, Gregory Hooker, wrote a paper about how the George W. Bush administration, contrary to the recommendations of many analysts, planned a small occupation force in Iraq and spent little time thinking about the consequences of the 2003 invasion.
Mr. Hooker also played a key role in the uprising against current coverage of the Islamic State.
Last year, Mr. Hooker's team, according to government sources, found that contrary to government claims, airstrikes on ISIL-controlled refineries would not have a significant impact on the financial position of the terrorist group, as these temporary refineries were set up to sell oil on the black market.
However, this finding was not published, the Times reported in September.
Centcom's then commander, General Lloyd J. Austin III, was criticized by members of the Legislature for his overly positive assessment of the war situation at a Senate hearing.
General Austin retired in April and was replaced at Central Command by General Joseph L. Votel.
