In the midst of the Olympic fury, the zen of trampolining
Wherever you are, no matter what time it is, it's the Olympics.
The events in Rio de Janeiro feel permanent and inevitable, a furious relay race between competition and ambition.
It's like the Olympic torch itself is a burning stick, passed from the armband to the swimmer to the gymnast to the triathlete.
You can't turn on the TV, read a newspaper, or listen to your neighbor in line at the coffee shop without hearing about Simone Biles, Katie Ledecky, or the fight between Michael Phelps and Chad Le Clos.
And then there's Logan Dooley.
Dooley, who is in the Olympics for the first time and a bunch of women with dimples, could have been one of those household names on prime time, built up by sponsors and feel-good TV commercials, if he was a swimmer, gymnast or even a fighter.
But Dooley, 28, from Lake Forest, California, is fighting for Olympic gold in the trampoline event.
The Olympic flame does not illuminate every event equally.
Further from the centre, partly in the shade, are the sports not generally recognized: air pistol shooting, archery, badminton, taekwondo.
We'll always have the breast swim and may it last.
But if I may make a modest argument for my particular favorite, let me draw attention to the discreet charm of the trampoline.
Although trampoline jumping has been an Olympic event since 2000, when it made its debut in Sydney, it has been so underrated for the past 16 years that many of the people I interviewed didn't even know it was an Olympic sport.
It could be regional ignorance.
Although the United States sent athletes to compete, it has never won a medal in trampoline jumping and until 2012 had no athlete make it to the final round.
The Chinese and Russians tend to split the prices for the men and the Chinese and Canadians the prices for the women.
Dong Dong from China and Rosie MacLennan from Canada will defend their gold medal from London this year.
Trampoline jumping has a certain outsider charm, partly because it sounds more appropriate to an unenlightened ear for a clown school than for the Olympics.
At this point, I should admit that I am not an expert, but just a grounded enthusiast.
It has the humor potential - the cartoonish trembling of its never-ending impact - but also the grace of gymnastics and diving, the two sports that essentially unite it.
The word "trampoline" comes from the Spanish El Trampolin, which means "jumpboard".
Aspiring winners jump on a giant trampoline, shoot up to nearly 30 feet into the air, and must make a series of falling movements (spins, stitches, and saltos) before landing on their feet.
They are graded according to the official Olympic programme by execution, difficulty and "flight time".
Thirty-two athletes from 17 countries, 16 men and 16 women, will compete in Rio.
The most common Olympic vector is straight.
Medal hopefuls must go on, faster, up and over, sometimes to the finish, sometimes back and forth, up and down the playing field, in their pursuit of gold.
They are not only chasing the finish line or the starting wall, but also another derogatory goal on television: the world or Olympic record.
The purposeful pursuit is noble, admirable, even fanatical - and it is enough to move even an onlooker to tears.
But it's also what I find a little tiresome even watching these games.
The trampoline offers a respite from that.
The trampoliner's vector is up.
Moving forward is not the goal.
He or she bounces off, seemingly weightless like an astronaut, goes up, then down, then effortlessly back up.
Here too, there is competition, not without difficulty, of course, but during the exercise there is no frantic attack on the target, no wolf in the distance, only the dreamy, elegant elimination of time and gravity.
It's as Zen as competition at the Olympics can be.
The women's qualifying and final rounds will be held on Friday afternoon, streaming at 1pm Eastern Time; the men's on Saturday, also at 1pm.
NBC will air the finals as part of an afternoon block on both days beginning at 2 p.m.
Amid the Olympic mania, they promise a quiet, pleasant moment, one that will probably be overlooked in the general tumult.
If the only way to raise awareness is to target and objectify male athletes, as the Wall Street Journal recently suggested, then Mr. Dooley is expecting his air-struggling new fan base.
"A generation protesting" in Ethiopia, Long an ally of the US
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Protesters demanding political change in Ethiopia have encountered violent government opposition.
Witnesses say dozens of protesters were killed in gun battles during clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia on the verge of collapse?
In the last decade, it has been one of the most stable countries in Africa, a solid ally of the West with a rapidly growing economy.
But in recent months, anti-government protests have rocked the country and spread to more and more areas.
Last week, thousands of people took to the streets demanding fundamental political change.
The government's response was ruthless, according to human rights organizations.
Witnesses said police shot and killed dozens of unarmed protesters.
Videos circulating about the protests, which are believed to date from late or early this year, show security personnel beating young people with sticks while they were forced to stand hand in hand against a wall.
The head of the UN human rights office is now demanding a thorough investigation.
"It has always been difficult to hold this country together and it will be even harder in the future", said Rashid Abdi, the Horn of Africa project manager of the International Crisis Group, a research group.
Ethiopia is the second most populous country in Africa after Nigeria and its stability is appreciated by the West.
U.S. military and intelligence agencies are working closely with the Ethiopians to combat terrorist threats beyond the region, particularly in Somalia.
Ethiopia's economy expanded at a remarkable pace.
Its infrastructure has improved dramatically - there is a new commuter train in the capital Addis Ababa.
The streets are usually quiet, safe and clean.
Although Ethiopia has been far from a model of democracy - human rights groups have consistently led the government's crackdown - opposition in the country has been curbed, with dissent effectively silenced.
Many were exiled or imprisoned, killed, or driven into the wilderness.
But that could change.
"If you oppress people and they have no other option but to protest, it breaks out", said Seyoum Teshome, a lecturer in central Ethiopia.
The whole youth is protesting.
A generation is protesting.
There are numerous complaints, covering everything from land use to the stranglehold on power of the ruling coalition.
After a widely criticized election last year, the ruling party and its allies won the last opposition seat and now control 100 percent of parliament.
At the same time, tensions are rising along the border with Eritrea, where a battle over the jagged, disputed line claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatists like the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, which have been more or less defeated in recent years, could take advantage of the turmoil and rearm.
Several factors explain why feelings of bitterness after years of limping are now exploding beneath the surface.
The first one seems harmless: smartphones.
It was only in recent years that many Ethiopians were able to communicate through social media as cheaper smartphones became more common and Internet services improved.
Even when the government blocks access to Facebook and Twitter, which it does at regular intervals, especially during protests, many people can still communicate through Internet proxies that hide their whereabouts.
Several young Ethiopians said they gathered to protest.
The second factor is that there is more solidarity between the Oromo and Amhara, the two largest ethnic groups in Ethiopia.
The Oromo and Amhara are not natural enemies.
For eons, the Amharas, who come from Ethiopia's predominantly Christian highlands, have thrived politically and economically while exploiting the Oromos, many of whom are Muslims and live in lowland areas.
But that's changing, too.
"We are in the process of coordinating under one umbrella", said Mulatu Gemechu, an Oromo leader.
The largest protests took place in Amhara and Oromo areas.
Many Amharas and Oromos feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, which makes up about 6 percent of the population and is dominant in the military, intelligence, commerce and politics.
The third reason for the unrest is the death of Meles Zenawi.
Meles, a former rebel leader, was Ethiopia's prime minister for 17 years until his death from an undisclosed illness in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could think of corners.
Analysts say he was particularly adept at spotting early signs of discontent and using special agents to process opponents and render them harmless.
"The current regime lacks this basic skill", said Mr Abdi, a conflict analyst.
Ethiopia's new Prime Minister, Hailemariam Desalegn, was chosen for relatively unclear reasons to take the place of Mr Meles.
Unlike Mr Meles, who came from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Mr Hailemariam comes from the south.
Analysts say he is not trusted by the Tigray-controlled security services.
Many fear that the result will be more bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia experienced such a riot was in 2005, after thousands protested against elections that analysts said were apparently foiled and then stolen by the government.
During the subsequent raids many protesters were killed, although fewer than in the previous months and this period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts praised Ethiopia's leaders for their visionary infrastructure planning, such as the new commuter train, and for their measurable progress in poverty alleviation.
But obviously this has not prevented the intensification of internal resentment in the Ethiopian government.
And it's taking on a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in Gondar, an Amharic city, attacked Tigray-run businesses, and hatred of Tigrayans is becoming more common on social media.
Analysts say the protests put the United States and other Western allies in a strange position.
The US government used Ethiopia as a base for drone flights over neighboring Somalia, although it recently announced that it was closing that base.
While the West clearly wants to support democracy, it does not want its ally to collapse in an already volatile area.
"This", said Mr. Abdi, "is a very thin ridge walk".
