Some 1.4 billion devices were sold, of which Samsung and Apple alone account for 555 million.
The worldwide turnover of the equipment is around 400 billion euros.
In addition, the business of countless app providers and telecommunications companies is doing well.
A whole industry has now emerged around the smartphone.
The breakthrough to the mass market came only in early 2007, when Apple CEO Steve Jobs announced the introduction of the iPhone at Mac World.
He promised three devices in one: a music player, a phone, and an Internet communicator, all easily operated via touch screen.
Apple's triumphal march began, and today the iPhone is still the company's most important product.
Nokia, Motorola and Blackberry, which dominated the market, had the rear end.
They finally disappeared, Blackberry's struggling.
Apple and Asian vendors like Samsung are now in charge.
The smartphone is a matter of course 20 years after its invention.
On average, every German now checks his cell phone 88 times a day.
"We all need to learn to put away our smartphones", said Janina Kugel, Siemens' board member for human resources.
Permanent accessibility is now considered a curse and a blessing at the same time.
