NASA climate model: Venus was once habitable
Venus was probably once habitable, according to projections from a new NASA climate model.
Scientists at NASA's Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model to discover the past of Venus using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to determine whether Venus, with its hot, waterless surface and CO2-dense atmosphere, could have once had Earth-like conditions.
Scientists have previously suggested that Venus' slow rotation could be explained by its dense atmosphere.
But the latest simulations suggest that Venus may have had a thin, Earth-like atmosphere and yet was slowly expanding.
The model also shed light on the topography of early Venus.
The planet probably had more dry areas than Earth, but it once had enough water and geographic variability to support life and protect it from rapid evaporation.
Early Venus also benefited from a sun that was 30 percent matter.
"In the GISS model simulation, Venus' slow rotation exposes its day side to the sun for almost two months", explained GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio in a press release.
This heats the surface and produces rain, which creates a thick layer of clouds, acting like an umbrella to shield the surface from much of the sun's heat.
The result is average temperatures that are several degrees cooler than Earth's today.
The model produced a history of Venus that is similar to the evolution previously assumed by planetary scientists.
Although it was probably habitable at one time, Venus was exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet light over the course of billions of years.
Their oceans evaporated and their water vapor was burned away by ultraviolet light.
When they escaped the hydrogen, all that was left was a thick atmosphere of carbon dioxide with a deadly greenhouse effect -- the Venus we know today.
The researchers shared the results of their new Venus climate model in Geophysical Research Letters.
