Kepler measures the rotation rate of stars in the Pleiades
The latest Kepler space telescope mission has helped astronomers to compile the most complete catalogue of rotation rates among the stars of the Pleiades.
The new data help astronomers to understand why stars in clusters rotate at different rates and how rotation periods are related to planet formation.
"We hope that by comparing our results with other star clusters, we can learn more about the relationship between a star's mass, its age, and even the history of its solar system", said Luisa Rebull, a researcher at Caltech's Infrared Processing and Analysis Center in Pasadena, in a news release.
The Pleiades star cluster is 445 light-years from Earth.
Many stars in this cluster, which formed about 125 million years ago, are now reaching adulthood.
They're spinning fastest now.
At peak rotation rates, these maturing stars emit large amounts of stellar winds.
Because these winds travel through the magnetic fields of the stars, they have a slowing effect on the stars.
When a star ages, its rate of rotation begins to slow.
Kepler measures the rate of rotation of each star by detecting the time between the appearance of a noticeable star spot -- like a sunspot.
The latest catalog of rotation rates suggests that more massive stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Rebull compares the stars to dancers, with larger stars spinning slower than smaller ones.
"In the 'ballet' of the Pleiades, we see that slow rotors tend to be more massive, whereas faster rotors tend to be very bright stars", Rebull said.
Because the Pleiades are so close, they serve as an ideal cosmic laboratory for comparing stellar qualities, such as rotation rates.
"The Pleiades cluster provides an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions, younger and older", Rebull said.
There's still a lot we want to learn about, like how, when and why stars slow down their rotation rates and hang up their dancing shoes, so to speak.
Rebull and her colleagues have reported extensively on their latest analysis of the rotation rates of the Pleiades in three newspaper reports, which will soon appear in the Astronomical Journal.
