How treacherous hackers extort ransom
Blackmail malware developers are now targeting companies - and succeeding.
According to a recent survey of 540 companies in North America, the United Kingdom, and Germany, conducted by malware protection specialist Malwarebytes, 40 percent of the companies surveyed were victims of a ransomware attack at least once, sometimes repeatedly, in the past 12 months.
In Germany, almost 20 percent of companies have been the target of ransomware extortion.
Forty percent of the victims willingly paid the ransom demanded by the perpetrators in order to regain access to the systems and data that were compromised.
The perpetrators are increasingly specializing their blackmail software in attacks on corporate networks, according to Malwarebytes' observations.
If they succeed, the potential ransom to be extorted is significantly higher than for private users.
"We are currently witnessing an alarmingly rapid evolution of malware", explains Malwarebytes CEO Marcin Kleczynski in an interview with Welt.
In 2008, most malware programs were still designed to send ads.
Then the perpetrators discovered blackmail software for themselves.
First, the target was private users, but the shift to corporate attacks has been alarmingly rapid in recent months.
Ransomware works in a simple pattern: Once active on a victim's computer, it specifically searches for recently modified files, such as Word, Excel, or database files, as well as archives of images and videos.
These files are encrypted by the ransomware and the originals are permanently deleted.
The software then presents the demands of the blackmailers.
To get the final encryption code to the files, the victims have to transfer money - usually in the form of the cryptocurrency Bitcoin.
But whereas private users are concerned with personal photo databases, companies are concerned with sensitive customer or project databases, without which production stops.
Accordingly, the damage is higher when a ransomware attacks.
22 percent of the German companies affected reported loss of revenue due to ransomware, 13 percent even had to completely cease business operations, in one case people's lives were in danger.
In Germany, hospitals have already been the victims of attacks on several occasions, where patients may be at acute risk of losing their medical records.
"We always tell the victims: Don't pay, you're only contributing to the problem", Kleczynski explains.
But 80 to 90 percent of the companies that pay get their data back.
It is difficult for managers to refuse the demands of the perpetrators in the face of a shutdown.
Hackers, in turn, know this and try everything to build a good reputation.
In a recent study, security researchers at F-Secure looked at user interfaces and contact with blackmailers and concluded that the attackers were actually trying to build some kind of customer service to make more money.
They explain to their victims in chat how to pay with Bitcoin, set up open support websites, or decrypt sample files for free.
And if individuals are redeemed after paying a few hundred euros, companies sometimes have to negotiate hard and pay five-figure sums to get their data back unencrypted.
Given the high and relatively low-risk potential of ransomware extortion, hackers are becoming more professional and sharing the work, explains security expert Chester Wisniewski of antivirus company Sophos: "A single person can write a ransomware within about a week".
However, it is more likely that it is three or four people.
The programmers then sell their malware in the form of a software kit to the actual blackmailers.
The malware kits that we've seen so far have been created by buying the malware itself, consulting and additional tools for a one-time, fixed price of between $1,000 and $10,000.
"A customization tool is included, so that smaller configurations, appearance and branding can be changed", says Wisniewski.
The blackmailers then look for more hackers to distribute the newly purchased software to the victims.
We live in a service economy.
So you log into one of the underground forums, buy the kit from one criminal, and then you have another one install the software on as many computers as possible.
Payment is per infected computer.
"Usually, the criminals then hire spammers to distribute it", explains Wisniewski.
The risk of ransomware is now known to many companies who are better at securing their data.
Over 50 percent of enterprise IT leaders in the Malwarebytes survey trust that file backups and scanner software can help prevent ransomware.
Accordingly, the perpetrators are already pursuing new strategies.
"When encryption alone is no longer a sufficient threat to successful hacking, attackers threaten to release sensitive data, such as customer lists or price lists", explains Malwarebytes CEO Marcin Kleczynski.
This means that the potential for damage is many times higher than before, depending on the type of data.
In the future, criminals could also target entirely new targets in the Internet of Things.
At the Defcon hacker conference, security researchers demonstrated how they could get a thermostat connected to the Internet under their control.
In the middle of winter, unlocking a blocked heater could be worth the ransom for many victims.
If criminals then block an entire production line in a factory in the future instead of heating, ransomware could also become an issue in Industry 4.0.
