Treatment options include behavioral changes, cognitive behavioral therapy, or medication - conventional sleeping pills only in exceptional cases and for a maximum of two weeks.
There are hardly any established sleep doctors in Germany, emphasizes Prof. Ingo Fietze, head of the interdisciplinary Sleep Medicine Centre at the Charité Universitaire Berlin.
That is why the first thing to do when you have sleep problems is to see your doctor, advises Weiss.
He can use tests to determine if the problems have a physical cause.
Who's going to the sleep lab, and what happens?
For example, doctors recommend a sleep lab test for snoring with respiratory arrest, for sick daytime tiredness, for sleepwalking, or if the cause of a sleep disorder cannot be found, explains Fietze.
You don't have to prepare for the exam.
You should spend the day normally.
"Please don't take a nap", says Fietze.
After you've wired it, you go to bed at your usual time.
In addition to the electrodes on the body, you wear a pair of goggles, a breast belt, and a finger sensor.
A camera on the ceiling also records the sleeping.
How can those affected cope?
There are quite a few screws you can use to get better sleep.
